  "prompt": "What are the major events that happened in 1997?",
  "response": "Several significant events occurred in 1997 across various fields, including politics, science, and culture. Here are some of the major highlights:\n\n1. **Hong Kong Handover**: On July 1, 1997, the United Kingdom handed over sovereignty of Hong Kong to China after 156 years of British rule. This marked the beginning of the \"one country, two systems\" principle.\n\n2. **Death of Princess Diana**: On August 31, 1997, Diana, Princess of Wales, died in a car crash in Paris. Her death prompted an outpouring of grief around the world and led to significant media coverage and discussions about the monarchy and media intrusion.\n\n3. **Financial Crisis in Asia**: The Asian Financial Crisis began in July 1997, starting in Thailand with the devaluation of the Thai baht. It had widespread consequences, leading to economic turmoil in several East Asian countries.\n\n4. **Protests in Indonesia**: Widespread protests led to the resignation of Indonesian President Suharto in May, ending his 31-year rule amid a backdrop of economic crisis and demands for democratic reforms.\n\n5. **The Launch of Netflix**: Founded in 1997, Netflix started as a DVD rental service, which would eventually evolve into a leading streaming platform, changing how people consume media.\n\n6. **The Discovery of the First Exoplanet**: The first confirmed exoplanet orbiting a sun-like star, 51 Pegasi b, was discovered in 1997, marking a significant milestone in the field of astronomy.\n\n7. **Mars Pathfinder Mission**: NASA's Mars Pathfinder successfully landed on Mars on July 4, 1997, and sent back a wealth of information and images, rekindling interest in planetary exploration.\n\n8. **Popular Culture**: The release of blockbuster films such as \"Titanic,\" which became the highest-grossing film of all time until it was surpassed years later. \n\n9. **The Birth of the First Test Tube Baby**: Louise Brown, the world\u2019s first test tube baby, celebrated her 20th birthday in July 1997, marking two decades since the groundbreaking in vitro fertilization technique became a reality.\n\n10. **The Kyoto Protocol**: In December 1997, the Kyoto Protocol was adopted at the UN Climate Change Conference in Kyoto, Japan, setting international targets for greenhouse gas emissions reduction.\n\nThese events shaped the political landscape, scientific progress, and cultural developments of the late 1990s and beyond.",
